    <segment id="1" parent="7" relname="preparation">
I accessed the article you referenced</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="13" relname="span"> and I agree with your assessment that intuitiveness 
should mean overall ease of use not just during the initial period.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="17" relname="span"> However, the article&apos;s 
study seemed to be based on a random set of students</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="16" relname="span"> and I wonder if the study itself 
might be flawed</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="8" relname="elaboration"> in that it did not start by determining what the user problem and work 
flow was about.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="14" relname="span"> I think that there are systems that are built for experts in certain fields, 
such as CAD/CAM,</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="12" relname="span"> where novices might be able to perform some tasks</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="10" relname="elaboration"> but without 
experience (expertise) in the field for which the application was designed will not be able 
to proceed too deeply into the use of the application.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="5" relname="evidence"> The article itself mentioned 
that &quot;experts&quot; will organize the compenents of their mental processes in larger &quot;chunks&quot;.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="15" relname="span"> 
To me that meant they may be sampling the wrong population - or too broad a 
population - for their study.
</segment>
